International community condemns massacres in Norway
2011-07-23 16:12:40 GMT
BEIJING, July 23 (Xinhua) -- More countries across the world Saturday expressed their condemnation toward Friday's heinous twin terror attacks in Norway, which have killed at least 92 people.Norwegian Prime Minister Jens Stoltenberg said what happened on Friday was a national tragedy, which Norway had not experienced since World War II.Stoltenberg said it was difficult to express in words how much sympathy he had for those affected.Chinese Premier Wen Jiabao extended condolences to Stoltenberg over the attacks.In his message, Wen condemned the violent twin attacks, and extended his condolences to the victims and deep sympathy to their families.Russian President Dmitry Medvedev has extended condolences to the Norwegian king and prime minister.In his message to King Harald, Medvedev said Russia sincerely empathized and stood in solidarity with the friendly people of Norway at this difficult time.In his message to Stoltenberg, Medvedev said Russia strongly condemned these "heinous" crimes, saying the organizers and perpetrators would be punished "to the fullest extent of law."British Prime Minister David Cameron expressed his outrage on Saturday at the horrific attacks, emphasizing that Britain will learn lessons from the tragedy."The loss of life in Norway has been absolutely horrific. It's on a scale that is frankly hard to comprehend," said Cameron during an interview."We'll want to make sure that we learn like others any lessons there are to learn about how to be more secure against horrific outrages like this," Cameron added.Polish President Bronislaw Komorowski, in a personal letter to King Harald, expressed shock at the attacks.The president, whose country took over the European Union's six-month rotating presidency in July, also offered his condolences to the families of the victims.The Polish Ministry of Foreign Affairs said the country was united in grief with the Norwegian people.Bahrain's foreign ministry expressed condemnation of such violent and criminal acts, which ran counter to any religion or human values.Cyprus President Demetris Christofias has sent a letter of condolences to Stoltenberg."It is with great shock and profound sorrow that we have received news of the heinous attacks in Norway," Christofias said in the letter."I wish to convey our deepest condolences to the government and the people of the Kingdom of Norway and especially to the families of the victims," Christofias said.Australian Prime Minister Julia Gillard joined the collective condemnation of the attacks.Gillard said Norway was a good friend and partner of Australia, and Australia condemned the brutal and shocking attacks."Our sorrow and concern are with the people of Norway and in particular with the families of those who have lost loved ones and those who have been injured."New Zealand acting Prime Minister Bill English said: "I'm shocked and saddened at the news of the bombing and shootings.""New Zealand joins with other countries in condemning these attacks on innocent people. Our thoughts and condolences are with the people of Norway at this time," English said.Greek Prime Minister George Papandreou contacted Stoltenberg a few hours after the deadly attacks, and expressed the strong support of the Greek people to Norway.Pakistani President Asif Ali Zardari strongly condemned the attacks.Zardari expressed his grief and shock over the loss of lives in the attacks and conveyed his condolences to the people and government of Norway.The president said Pakistan, as a front-line state in the fight against terrorism, condemned and abhored all forms of terrorism and militancy as well as the acts of terrorism wherever they happen.Deputy Philippine presidential spokesperson Abigal Valte said, "We wish to extend our condolences to the families of those who were killed in the attack."The day of killing began when a bomb exploded in downtown Oslo near government offices, killing seven people and injuring more than 19 others. Hours later, a gunman dressed in a police uniform opened fire at a youth camp run by Norway's ruling political party on Utoya, an island south of Oslo, killing at least 85 people. 
